<DOC><DOCNO> AP880430-0166 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0119EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Mengistu     04-30 0179</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Mengistu,0194</SECOND><HEAD>Mengistu Blames Africa's Internal Struggles On Outside Forces</HEAD><DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Africa's limited resources arebeing exhausted by wars with groups supported by enemies of Africa,President Mengistu Haile Mariam said Friday.   ``Some external forces inimical to Africa have posed obstaclescompelling African states to divert their resources and effort awayfrom socio-economic development,'' Mengistu said at a ceremonymarking the 30th anniversary of the U.N. Economic Commission forAfrica, which has headquarters in Addis Ababa.   Mengistu did not name the outside enemies he held responsiblefor Africa's internal struggles, but said they ``are challengingthe sovereignty and territorial integrity of African states. Africashould in one voice, strongly condemn them and tell them, hands offour continent.''   His Soviet-backed Marxist government is fighting rebel groups inEthiopia's northernmost provinces of Eritrea and Tigre.   Eritrea has Africa's longest civil war, a 27-year secessionistfight by the Eritrean People's Liberation Front. In Tigre, south ofEritrea, the Tigre People's Liberation Front has been fighting for14 years.   Mengistu's government refers to the guerrillas as bandits.</TEXT></DOC>